AGI -&nbsp;"European countries" are willing to send troops to Ukraine to ensure compliance with a possible peace agreement with Russia. The French President Emmanuel Macron at the end of the 31 'volenterosis' summit meeting at the Elysée raises the proposal to send European soldiers to ensure any future agreements between Kiev and Moscow. Macron > confirms that on this "unanimous vote", and it is known that several countries including Italy have already made known that they do not intend to participate in the mission.
But unanimity is not necessary, adds the French president, "we will go ahead and we will work. So there will certainly be a reassurance force with different European countries that will enslave." The "reinsurance forces" > do not necessarily have to be peacekeeping forces, nor to settle "on the contact line" or replace the Ukrainian armed forces, adds Macron: the purpose would be to provide Kiev "long-term support and a deterrent against potential Russian aggression".
The theme, however, is to come, adds, and will only be discussed when an understanding will be reached that at the moment appears far away. "Russia pretends to negotiate," says the French President, in reality does not want peace. That is why the leaders gathered at the Elysée agreed that removing sanctions in Moscow would now be a mistake. In the meantime, Macron insists, it is necessary to strengthen the position of Kiev, politically and militarily. This is why Paris and London will send a joint mission to Ukraine to work on strengthening the army.
"In three or four weeks we will have a fairly precise plan of action on these two issues, the configuration of the Ukrainian army and the reinsurance forces," said the French President, who together with British Prime Minister Keir Starmer, will lead the efforts of the coalition that includes European states, Canada and to which EU and NATO institutions participate. "The British Prime Minister and I are sending our Chiefs of Staff of Defence to send our French-British teams to Ukraine in the coming days to prepare the configuration of what will be the Ukrainian army of tomorrow," said Macron.
Starmer also confirms the line: "We brought together 30 countries which this morning openly declared that it was long since they had not seen such a strong Europe, and by that I mean the continent, not the European institutions," said the British Prime Minister, who spoke of a European "mobilization" for peace "without precedent for decades". Full support in Kiev also came from Germany: the outgoing chancellor Olaf Scholz published a photo next to Volodymyr Zelensky and added: "We will be alongside Ukraine until it is necessary." &nbsp;
<h2> Meloni, no of Italy to military force
The President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni, at the top of the 'volenterosis', reiterated - explains a note of Palazzo Chigi - that there is no national participation in any military force on the ground.&nbsp;
<h2>Melons at the Paris Summit, involve the US in meetings</h2>
The President of the Council hoped - adds the note - the involvement of an American delegation to the next coordination meeting. Meloni stresses the importance of continuing to work with the United States to stop the conflict and reach a peace that assures the sovereignty and security of Ukraine.
<h2>Melons, extend ceasefire to schools and hospitals
The President of the Council indicated how important it is now to be able to extend the partial ceasefire to civil infrastructure, such as schools and hospitals, with the aim of reaching a total ceasefire, adds the note.&nbsp;
